@ajsteven130 Thanks for great advice
@all Using python instead of ipython5 with emacs seems like a better solution for now.

What works for me is that I can copy now multiple lines into the python buffer and they get executed.
That wasn't the case when using ipython. However, line-by-line sending does not work in Emacs(elpy) at the moment of writing I encounter this bug [#907](https://github.com/jorgenschaefer/elpy/issues/907) and suggested alternative C-M-x does not work as expected as well. Kind of stucked now with copying blocks of code, but better than nothing.

OK, so the line breaks are going through as 13, which is carriage return. But that's the same as what happens when I press enter in a terminal, and prompt_toolkit specifically [handles that](https://github.com/jonathanslenders/python-prompt-toolkit/blob/9b6cd5adfc6892e0bf9251366e03041a45885430/prompt_toolkit/terminal/vt100_input.py#L393).

Is your prompt_toolkit up to date?

@jonathanslenders, might you have a moment to investigate this? Thanks!
